<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-help-when-to-call-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">What a ProAdvisor is for &mdash; and what they&rsquo;re not.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p id="qb-help-when-to-call-in-brief-text">A Certified QuickBooks ProAdvisor is an accounting professional certified by Intuit to set up, repair, and run QuickBooks &mdash; the operational work that lives <em>inside your books</em>. You call one when the numbers themselves need help: the file is behind or messy, reconciliation won&rsquo;t tie, you need a cleanup ahead of a deadline, you&rsquo;re standing up or moving a QuickBooks file, or you simply need books you can trust. The deciding question is always &ldquo;is the problem in the <em>accounting</em>?&rdquo; &mdash; if so, it&rsquo;s a ProAdvisor call.</p>
      <p>What a ProAdvisor is <em>not</em> is Intuit. An independent firm can&rsquo;t reach into your Intuit account, reset your login, change your subscription or billing, or patch a software bug &mdash; those are Intuit&rsquo;s to handle, and trying to route them to us only slows you down. The honest split below keeps the two apart: the situations that genuinely warrant a ProAdvisor, the loudest call-now signals, and exactly what to do first &mdash; including when the right move is to call Intuit instead.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

